state of the thickly inhabited villages, and to the keeping the streets and roads of the district in a state available for trafic. in the absence of proper drains for carrying off stagnant water and the injury inflicted on the district through the contamination of be river by filth and oftal poured into it from the sater-house. your council found themsel barred by want of funds not only from instalment on account of the grant from the land fund in aid of district councils revenues made on the supplementary estimates for 1853. anxious to commence the cutting of drains, &c. before the ground became hardened by the summer droughts, and while yet labour might be withdrawn for the purpose without in:erfering with harvest work, your council again applied to government for a further messrs crawford brothers the very moderate amount demanded by them for the right of way through their property, in continuation of this road. the line has been proclaimed, surveyed, and marked off, in accordance with the provisions of the road act. negociations have been entere, into for the purchase of materials for fencing. i is estimated that the cost of opening this line including fencing, will amount to nearly £40. and your council mindful of the pledge given the public meeting, when the rate was adopted, to the effect that the funds collected in each locality should as far as possible be MORRISON'S ELECTION.PUBLIC MEETING AT SORELL.ANUMEROUS and most respectably attended meeting of the electors of the proposed electoral district of Sorell was held at the Blue Bell Inn, Sorell, on the 12th instant, to receive Mr. Atkin Morrison, the representative elect of the district, and to adopt much measures as might be requisite to ensure his return. The electors Assembled in great numbers, even from the distant parts of the district; and the large room was crowded to excess. An elegant though substantial and well provided repast was provided, at which W. H. Glover, jun., Esq., presided, supported by R, Crocker, E.4„as The usual loyal tons were given, when the President gave„Our future Representative Askin Morrison, Eng." Mr. Gilover passed merited eulogium upon Mr. Morrison, as man who had the clearperception of the wants of the colony, and who had during a mojourn of nearly 25 years in it, by his various efforts in the development of its resources and the improvement of its facilities of internal access and intercourse, proved his sagacity and foreight ;-as one who had left no opportunity animproved wherein his private fortune or his exertions could be brought to bear in its behalf and whose immonse transactions in commerce, in agriculture, and in whaling give the surest gunerantee that even on the ground of personal interest alone, he must have the welfare of the colony at heart, the interests of which were so extensively and so inseparably connected with his own :—alaman, moreover, whose liberal and onlightened principles rendered him peculiarly adapted to represent any community to which food goverment was desirable, or to which British rights and liberty were dear Mr. Glover also took occasion to deprecate the existence or encouragement of any feeling of animosity or ill-will on the part of the supporters of either Mr. Morrison or the formerly rival candidate, Mr. Gregonexprening it as the earnent hope and expectation of every intelligent person, that Mr. Morrison and Mr. Gregson would, on the advocates of all liberal and enlightened views, be found co-operating in the new Legislature in supporting and promoting those principles. The hoalh was drunk with enthusiastic and prolonged appinune. Mr. Morrison rose to return thanks, and referred them to their own experience of his career during the long period he had been known in the colony Throughout that career he had never attached himselt' to any party or political faction: whatever he had said or done had been diated by his own independent consciencelle had constantly availed himself of every opportunity that came within the influence of his means or his efforts to advance the interests of the colony. But he would give no pledgeshe would bind himself to no measures, if he entered that Assembly as a Representative, it would be unpledged unlettered, except by one single pledge-namely, that be would use his utmost exertion and his best judgment, independently and conscientiously, for the good of the colony; Mr. Morrison a luded to the fact, that he had a vast capital employed in agriculture in commerce-in whaling; and that, of all the proceeds and income of these concerns, he did not send one furthout of the colony. Hewent no money to England to pay the interest of Britisk borrored capital Nor was it his ultimate intention that his money should ever leave the shores of Van Diemen's Land: he had spent his best days in the Island, and he intended to be buried in its soil. Mr. Morrison sat down amidenthusiastic cheering and the social meeting terminated. Mr. W. H. Glover, jun., was again voted to the chair, and having opened the public meeting. It was proposed by Mr. C. A. Glover and seconded by Mr. Carte "That this meeting, having heard the declaration of Aolin Morrison, E., as to his political sentiments, is confirmed in its opinion as to his fitness to represent the district of Sorell in the forthcoming Legislature; and accordingly resolves that it is not desirable that he should be returned as representative of the district." Mi Hodgson, of Richmond, rose to interrogate Mr. Morrison as to his views on the transportation question, Considerable interruption ensued. Whenience was obtained, the Chairman stated that he could on authority assert that Mr. Morrison was an opponent of transportation ; that he (the Chairman) was an ultratitransportationist; and that, if he had not good grounds for the conviction of Mr. Morrison's views, he would never have given him A vote or promoted his return. Mr. Hodgson." I wish to hear it from Mr. Morrison's own lips. Inokasimple question and I want nniple answer." Mr. Morrison stated that he had not come forward by his own choice the office was none of his seeking :-that he had been requested by the inhabitants to allow himself to be put nomination. He attached himself to no party or political creed, and would pledge itself to nothing but to promote the good of the colony according to his best judgment and ability. He had been accused of getting up a petition in favour of transportation ; whilst, on the contrary, he had really and actually been the bearer of one of the antitransportation petitions (which he received from Mr. Pitcairn), and had obtained many signatures to it during a journey into the interior. Mr. Hodgson persisting in his questions, the Chairman ruled that he was out of order:-that, if he had anything to submit to the meeting, he must propose it as a resolution, or an amendment to the one already road. Mr. Hodgsonchcu proposed as an amendment, seconded by Mr. Kearney. "That tho meeting do adjourn until the electoral district be defined by the Council; and that when that fact shall become known, public meeting of electon be called." Mr. Hodgaon having obtained, with some diffully, a patient hearing in support of his amendment, it was put to the meeting, when about oix hands were shown in its favour out of nearly 300 persone present Mr. R. Cracker next proposed (seconded by Mr. Robert Doctor, and carried in the same That it is due to Mr. Morrison, from this meeting to express its entire satisfaction with the explanation of his sentiments given by that gentleman; and this meeting hereby accordingly Under to him its acknowledgment of the same." STEPEN, and Mr. ROBERT JOHNSON DROSPECTUS OF A CHURCH OY ENGLAND COLLEGE INOONNEXION WITH THE UNIVERSITY OF SYDNEY. The Legislature of this colony, by the foundation and munificent endowment of the UNIVERSITY OF SYDNEY, having provided an Institution in which secular knowledge of the highest order may be required, but from which, by the terms of its constitution, Religious instruction is excluded, it has become • matter of deep importance that members of the Church of England, by the establishment of a College of their own, in connexion with the University, (as contemplate by the Act or to incorporation.) should be enabled to Tail themselves of the advantage time ffered. It in proposed to establish, therefore, in permanentaliance with the Sydney Universt#} Church of England College, to be eilled QURAN', COLLBOX; in which systematic Religious instruction, domestic supervision, and moral discipline, with elementary teaching and efficient assistancomÎpreparing for the University Lectures and Bxaminations, shall be provided for Students of the Univer aity, whose Guardians or Parents may desire to secure such advantages for them And thus, while the acquisition by them of all other Useful Knowledke will be facilitated, and that union of the Tutorial and Professorial systems be Attained, which is so important in Academical Education, the great object will be kept in view of Instilling into their minds & reverence for the doctrines and tenets of our Church : and Learning will be CODsociated, all it ever should be, to the service and honour of God. With these views, the following Plan and Arrangement (subject to modification by the subscribers hereafter) are proposed 1. That College Buildings shall be erected in the vicinity of Sydney; to consist of a Hall, Chapel, and Library, with residences for a Wardenad BabWarden, and rooms for about forty Studenta2. That the government of the College shall be vented in a Council, to consist of the War den and six fellows: 3. That the Metropolitan Bishop shall be Vini. tor of the College 4. That the Council shall draw up Rules, (with power to amend them, from time time, may be thought expedient,) for the management of the College, and the order of all thing therein the furtherance of true Religion and Learning. 6. That the Warden, who shall be Clergs. man in Prienta' Orders, shall be appointed by the six Pollow and the SubWarden be appointed by the Warden, subject to their approva! 6. That there shall be twenty-four Follows be longing to the College of whom eight shall be Clergymen in Priest"' Orders. That the first twenty-four Follows shall be elected by the Subscribers and that al Vacancies in their number, by resignation or otherwise, shall be supplied by Graduates of the University continuing on the books of the College, 8. Provided that, until there shall be twenty such Graduates of the least, Vacancies among the Yellows shall be supplied by the remaining Felow; by election, in such manner as they may appoint 9. That the siz Felow members of the Council, who shall be called Senior Followo shall be elected by the twenty four Follows, from their own body. All Vacancies being supplied in like manner. - That, of the Senior Follows, three shall be Clergymen in Prieau Orden, and Laymen; and that they shall, every second year (oroftener if needbe),elect Bursar who mall have the control and administration of the revenues and disbursements of the College The Burser to be always capable of re-election, 11. That the Wardens (aubject to any rules made by the Council) shall have the general superintendence and control of the Stu dents, and of the Institution. 12. That arrangements shall be made, even tually, for the establishment of School, in immediate connection with the College; under such regulations, and supervision, the Council shall appoint. Thay an Act shall be sought from the Legislature for the permanent settlement and continuance of the College, upon the foundation, and for the purposcubere indianted : by incorporation, or otherwise, may be thought most desirable. In circulating the foregoing Prospectus of Church of England College, the Committee appointed at the Public Meeting held to promote to establishment, having given the subject their mature and anxious attention, and being Intified of the perfect practicability, a well as of the propriety and urgency of the object, earnestly invite co-operation in their design. The Commitee submit it for support, in the pursunion that a large portion of the Community will readly unite with them the advancement of principles, and the promotion of #system, within this colony, which have for eges been so conducive to the properity, the moral greatness, and the gory of England. They are anxioun, for the Members of their Church, to take advantage of the opportunity held out to them by the Legislature, of requiring instruction in the highest branches of secular learning: under Professors so distinguished, and admirably qualified in their respective departments, as those who now all the Chains in the Sydney University. But Church men, bowover influenced by such considerations, for that in the University one thing, the most sential, is yet wanting ; and they desire that, in this Colony as in England, mental improvement and Religion should move together, hand in hand. With such view, the establishment of an Institution to be called "Queen'. Coller'" has been projected, in connexion with the University and the Committee truating to the cordial sympathy of those interested in the undertaking, solicit subscriptions towards the object. On the amount so raised, will materially depend the extent of the undowment, which will be doubtless contributed by the Government and Legislature. The Committee, therefore, deeply sensible of the importance of this movement, trust that it will be met by prompt and generous aanistance. It will be observed, that the Prospectus contemplates the erection of Buidinp; and the Committee confidently expect that sufficient fund will be received, not for that object only but for a liberal endowment of the College. It is hoped, however, that arrangements may at once made, for the reception of Studenta attending the University, and their moral and religious supervision, by Clergymen willing to undertake that duty; or by other competent perons. paragraphs.context: Î________________  TO THE ELECTORS OF WEST ADELAIDE. Gentlemen As a candidate for your District I beg to state that the following is shortly my political creed, which I will amplify at the various public meetings LAW REPORM.-I advocate that the mailnery of the Local Court (which for years has worked admirably), with additions to most proceedings in Equity, bo extended to the Supreme Court, instead of adopting the experimental Judionture Act, the satisfactory working of which in England has yet to be proved I would also allow only one appeal from any judicial decision. IKBOLVENT LAW.-I am of opinion that the State should interfereas little as possible between creditors and their debton. I would therefore have machinery sufficient to place the assets of debtor in the bands of his creditors. A Registrar, to be approved by the Chamber of Commerce, and a small staff of assistanta, could do all tho work necesary. A majority of creditors should bind the minority, and fraudu.lent insolventa tried by & Jury. TRIAL BY JURY. I would support an amendment of the law to enable a majority of a Jury to returnavoid-in all cases. REAL PROPERTY ACT.-It is a popular fallacy to suppose that my profession oppose this very Decessary and useful Act. Most of us bold our property and practis under it. I will preserve the fundamental principles of this Act in their integrity, and do all I can to make the Act perfect. TAXATION. As were hearily taxed for everything we use and consime, I will endeavour to shift a portion of the burden on to the shoul. ders of Absentees. LAND LAW_A, I believe the answer to the great cry of "What shall we do with oursons!" is "Make them farmers," I would have the land offered at £1 per acre without interests are for each bolding extended to 1,000 acreslong credit given, and compulsory residence insistod upon so that the farmer may grow mutton, beef and wool in aduition to grain, IMMIGRATION.—Every facility should be given for colonists to get out their friends and relations, thus securing those wo pay for and amply supplying the wants of the country. POSTAGE AND TELEGRAPBS.-We are behind the age not adopting & penny postage and sixpenny telegrams throughout the colony. EDUCTION should be free, because I do not think the small payment, which it would be difficult to fix, would make a great reduction in the cont. Aud as I am of opinion that Justion losseps crime, we would save largely in other way. The Bible should be read schools, but the various religious views of our fellow-colonists are entitled to respect, and all should be allowed to participate in the Government sid as far supracticable. upon any other subjects I shall be happy to express my opinions at the meetings of Electors already advertised. I am, Gentlemen, Your obedient servant, 3520 WM. R. WIGLEY.

paragraphs.context: Î________________  THE GET PARLIAMENT. LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL. WEDNESDAY, JANTARY 231LD. The President took his seat at 4 o'clock. The Hon. Sir Charles Saden mored—That an address be presented to Her Majesty, setting forth the facts and circumstances of the present Crisis, and praying that such instructions may be given to the Governor) will secure the Constitutional Government of this colony;" and in addition he moved that the Committee consist of Mosers Balfour and Sargood, Sir Samuel Wilson, and the mover. He remarked that the circumstances under which he asked the Council to agree to the address were patent to the country. On the 6th inst. Government Gazetle was published announcing that the County Court Judges and the Police Magistrates had been dismised. Cominent had been made upon the subject, and general indignation at the action taken had been expressed by the public outside. The very silence of the people of the colony was omninous, and he considered that the citizens of Melbourne would, by some great meeting, express their in1dignation at the revolact which had been perpetrated by the Government. Words failed him to express the regret be folk at the upusual course which had been adopted by the present Government. The motion was agreed to, and the House adjourned to draw up the address. On the House Testing The Hon. Sir Charles Sinden brought up the address The address was merely a reiteration of former addresses to the Governor. It stated that in the opinion of the House trade was paralysed, the inforior Courts of Justice had been suspended, the whole country had been plunged into confusion, the happiness of the colonists had been sacrificer, and the action of the Government had resulted in misery and great disatisfaction to the House and to the colony at large The address was adopted, and the President was requested by the House to present the document to his Excellency that evening, so that it miglit be despatched by the out going mail. On the motion of tho kon. Sir Charles Saden, the House adjourned till Tuesday.

Lipsett) in the chair. The ministers of the different congregations and several other gentlemen luowa to take a warm interest in the cause were present. Mr. Pearce, sen„laid on the table copies of petition to the Legislative Council against tampering with the Act, which he had received from Mr. Nicholoon, of Mounta The business was mostly of conversational character. Some were favourable to a general meeting in connection with the election of members for the Legislative Council and the introduction of the other topic as part of the business, but as it was pointed out that very lltle probability existed of the presence of any of the candidates, it was finally decided to call a public meeting in the hall of the Institute, when the subject could be throughly ventilsted. Î________________  The Seek'flews. TunACCLIMATIZATION SOCIETYA meeting of the Council of this anciety Pran held on Friday. August 8, at the office of the Hon. Henry Scott, M.LO. There were present the Hon. Henry Scott, M.L.O. (in the chair), Sir John Morphett, the Hon. Joseph Fisher, M.L.O. Messrs. W. J. Magarey. M.P., W. A. B. WestErskine, M.P., George Hamilton, J.P., Abrahame, J P., and R.Š.Minchin (the Hon. Secretary). Apologies for non-attendance were received from His Honor the Chief Justice and Mr. Goyder. A letter was read from the Salmon Commissioners in Tasmania, informing the Council that the trout Ova would be shipped for Adelaide during the first week in August, Mr. Blackwood, of the firm of Meanrs. McMeckan, Blackwood, & Co., of Melbourne, wrot expressing his great willingness to assist the Society by every means in his power. The Secretary to write and thank Mr. Blackwood. It was resolved that the future meetings of the Council be held monthly, and on the Friday following the departure of the Englishmail. The Council were of opinion that the humblebee should be introduced into the colony at as early date as possible. It was resolved that the purch at present in the care of Mr. Magarey be liberated in the reservoirs, provided the Government raise no objection. On the proposition of Sir John Morphett, seconded by Mr. Hamilton, the Becretary was instructed to write to Dr. Mayo, and request his attendance at the meetings of the Council. The Secretary of the Acclimatization Society has informed as that large quantity of browntrontove has arrived by the South Australian from Tasmania for the Society. WANTS OF THE HUNDRED OF PALACKR_ Mr P. B. Coglin, M.P., waited on the Commissioner of Orown Lands on Wednesday, August 13, and presented the following petition, signed by eighty-four residents in the Hundred of Palmer-"That your memorialists are put to great inconvenience in consequence of the road lately surveyed, leading north-West from the township of Stephenston, not being surveyed through Section 57; that a letter, dated January 15, received from the Surveyor-General's Office, stated that the road would be attended to, and crossing made over the Willochra Creek; that the said section (57) is Government property, and now leased to Mr. Counsell. Your memorialist therefore humbly pray that you will cause the aforesaid road to be surveyed through Section 57 to the twenty-chain road immediately west of it, and cause a crossing to be made over the Willochra Creek." The Commissioner promised Mr. Ooglin that he would look into the matter. On the same date Mr. Ooglin waited on the Attorney-General and presented & petition to him asking him to appoint a Justice of the Peace at the Hundred of Palmer, and recommending Mr. J. C. Symons. Mr. Bundey said he would consider the matter. DAP OF WATER AT WOOL BAY.-Mr. G. E. Buttfield writes to say that at the meeting held at Pickering in reference to jetty accommodation there bestated that the depth of water at Wool Bay was eight feet, dot forty-eight feet as published. TEROWIRAND PICHIRICH RAILWAY.-Mr. P. B Coglin, M.P., one of the members for the District of Flinders, waited on the Commissioner of Public Works on Wednesday, August 13, and presented the following petition from eighty-seven residents of the Hundred of Palmer, County Newcastle :—" That your petitioners have policed with much regret that the Terowie and Pichinch Railway is not being brought to the township of Stephenston; that the aforesaid township is in a direct line from Conatto Gap to Quom; that nearly all the land in thin hundred is selected, that & vant are is under crop, and that an imme-quantity of wbest will be grown on the Palmer Plain; that if the above railway does not come to Stephenston your petitioners will be necessitated to take their produce, over a very bad road, to Quorn, and large sum of money will be required Annely to keep the same in repair. Your petitionera, therefore, humbly pray that you will cause the Terowie and Pichinch Railway to come to the towpabip of Stephenston." The Commissioner will he would give the matter his direful consideration. DRATHOY JAMES WALLACH.The friends of Mr. James Wallace will be sorry to hear of his death, which occurred at Peterhead, Scotland, on Saturday, June 28. It will be remembered that Mr. Wallace came to the colony some nine or ten years ago, in company, we think, with Mr. Morrell and Mr. A. Harvey, for the purpose of making arrangements with the Government for the construction of a railway Derth of Port Augusta on the guarantee principle. The scheme, however, fell through, and Mr. Wallace returned to Scotland. He retired shortly afterwards from business, and lived quietly Dear Peterboad. His wife died some four years ago, and the deceased Deveralled from the effects of the event. ACCIDENTATAPPILA YARROWIB.-An accident happened at Appils Yarrowie, on August 12, to a son of Mr. William Blight, farmer, which fortunately did not prove fatal A colt was being roped in the stock yards, and the boy was standing outside leading against the raila, when suddenly.nimalkicked between the rails, striking the lad over the right eve, and inflicting severegash. Dr. Willy Waid prompt attendance, and sitehed up the wound. The sufferer is progressing favourably towards recovery MALPAS'S PATENT　COMPOUND.We have been shown a piece of wood which by the aid of Malpan's Patent Compound has withstood tbe attacks of ants for the last five years, and is as sound now as ever it was. It was placed on an antil which was awarming with insects; but all that they did was to put kind of varish around the timber, which itself remained uninjured. The specimen, which is to be sent to the Sydney Exhibition, may be seen at the office of the South Australian Advertising Company. POLICE STATION FOR HAMLBY BRIDG.-Mr. Bright, M.P., waited on the Attorney-General on Tuesday, August 12, and presented « numerously signed memorial from inhabitants of Hamley Bridge and its neighbourhood, praying for the erection of a Police Station in that locality. The Minister promised to obtain & report as to the necessity which existed for a compliance with the prayer of the memorialista, and said he would afterwards confer with his colleagues on the subject. TE HARBINGER.-Messrs. J. Silling & Cobave received & cablegram announcing the arrivalt London of this vessel, which left Port Adelaide on March 27. BAILWAY INSPECTION.-On Monday e Hon. G. O. Hawker (the Commissioner of Public Works), Mr. Higinbotham (the Victorian Engineer), Mr. H. O. Mais (the Engineer-in-Chief), with some other officials, visited the North-West Bend by special train, the object, we believe, being to enable Mr. Higinbotham to inspect and report on the newly constructed line. It is understood that the latter gentleman apenaka very favourably of the railway. Dalton, of Adelaide. When finished the hall will, it is said, be quite equal to say out of Adelaide. Thx COPPER MARKET IN ENGLAND.-From the London Mining Journal of June 28 note the following :—'Sellers continurmer in their quotations, and were it not for the unsatisfactory turu which the Indian exchange has taken slightly better prices might ere this have been obtainable. It seems almost as though the late of the market for this metál is doomed, for whenever there has been any chance of little sport taking place in prices something has invariably turned up to check the advance. From time time there have been many fale starts to secure higher prices, but sellers have never since the downward torn commenced soceeded in maintaining Boy advance more than for a very abort time, but have constantly had to return to their former rates. It is greatly to be hoped, however, that the attemptarise which is now being made will not be altogether fruitles, and that advanced rates may soon be established throughout the trade, for up to the present time the only consulation left to sellers is that owing to the reduced prices quotations must have declined to about their minimum. Itreets, however, mainly with producers; if they restrict their future production then higher prices will soon be brought about; but if, on the other band, they continue to send forward wupplies a freely as they have been doing, then doubtlesalower priceacre long will have again to be accepted. At the public ticketing held Isat Tuesday at Swansea 1,788 tons fore were sold at average of 10s. 6d. per int."
